(6749, 10, 1, 5, '2015-11-23', 'Nice product for its price Have been using 2 of them for more than a year. Nice product for its price.'),
(6750, 9, 1, 5, '2015-01-22', 'This Brewer is a Game Changer at My House! After my Keurig was finally showing signs of being on its last leg after several years, I decided it was time for a new coffee maker. When I bought the Keurig, I was really the only one in the house who drank drip coffee, so it made sense to get a single-cup brewer. Now that my daughter is in college (and basically lives on coffee) and my other daughter has started drinking a cup in the mornings, too, I decided maybe it was time to say goodbye to the single-cup style and move on to a full brewer again. Not to mention that the newer Keurigs now require you to buy and use only their K-Cups (I never bought K-Cups, but instead ground my own beans and used a reusable K-Cup filter). Anyway, enough about that. The point is, it was time for an upgrade! After doing a lot of research on different types of brewers, I decided the best option for us would be something that would allow for single servings over a two or three hour period (we all wake up at different times in the mornings), but without the hassle of a glass carafe that would definitely break eventually, or a thermal carafe that often leaves coffee tasting a bit metallic. I also wanted something that would let me brew a small amount of coffee if needed (1 to 4 cups), more at other times (6 to 12 cups), and could keep the coffee warm without burning it, like the glass-carafe style brewers seem to do. Finally, I found the DCC-3000, and after using it for a few days, I have to say I\'m really impressed with this machine! It\'s been a total game changer around here! Flavor - The Cuisinart brews a lovely cup of coffee, with plenty of flavor and no burnt taste even after it\'s been kept warm for a couple of hours. This is HUGE, since I work from home on occasion and like to sip on coffee throughout the morning. Granted, the coffee I was drinking before this came from a Keurig machine (again, with my own, freshly ground beans, not pre-packaged K-Cups, which I find pretty tasteless and bland), so it\'s not like I\'m coming to this after using a high-end, coffee-enthusiast-style machine or anything. Compared to your average kitchen brewer, though, the flavor from the Cuisinart is exceptional, especially once you get the right grounds-to-water ratio right. Coffee brews hot and stays hot for hours, without tasting burnt. Keep in mind that your choice of coffee will factor into the flavor, as well. I use my favorite premium coffee (Stumptown or Cafe Vita usually) and grind it fresh for each pot. Your mileage may vary, depending on what you\'re using. Ease of Use - I didn\'t even need to reference the instructions to set this up and get a brew going when I first purchased it. Easy to brew a pot of coffee and easy to program for auto-brewing. It\'s all pretty straight-forward if you\'ve ever used a coffee machine before. Water, grounds, turn it on, boom - coffee. Features - I love having the actuator that allows us to fill our cups however full we want them, one cup at a time, and the light is handy first thing in the morning when filling our mugs. It\'s a nice touch. The coffee gauge on the front is also an excellent feature, and so far I\'ve had no issues with it not working. I like that I can tell, at a glance, how much coffee is left. The removable water reservoir is great, and means I don\'t have to fill another container with water to fill the machine. Drip tray works great and I don\'t have any leaking on my countertops, even with pretty heavy use. Auto-brew is a LIFESAVER in my house, because we all get to wake up to a fresh, piping hot pot of coffee every morning, with minimal effort. Cleaning - Super easy to clean. The brew basket, reusable filter and coffee reservoir are easy to remove and wash, and the \"Clean\" feature on the machine makes it easy to give the nozzles and whatnot a quick rinse between uses (and only uses about a cup of water), so everything stays clean with minimal effort. Quality - This isn\'t a high-end, $500 machine, but the build quality seems great so far. It looks nice on the counter, and nothing feels flimsy or cheap. I\'m happy with the quality. The only real thing I would change about this machine, if I could, would be having a water reservoir that stores the water and only uses as much as needed for however many cups I\'m making. The Breville You Brew has that feature (and also grinds your beans for you), but also costs $250. For me, the price of the Cuisinart is well worth the very mild inconvenience of having to fill the tank each night before turning on the auto-brew feature. If you\'re looking for a machine that brews a great cup of coffee and has a few really nice added features, the DCC-3000 is a good choice. I definitely recommend it!'),
